{{Infobox NRHP | name = Nela Park | image = Nela_Park_Building_307.jpg | caption = Nela Park, Building 307 | location = Entrance at 1901 Noble Rd., East Cleveland, Ohio 44112 | locmapin = Ohio#USA | coordinates = {{coord|41|32|28|N|81|33|39|W|display=inline,title}} | area = | built = 1911-1924 | architect = Frank E, Wallis | architecture = | added = 1975 | designated_other1_name= | designated_other1_date= | designated_other1_abbr= | designated_other1_link= | designated_other1_color= #aaccff | refnum = 75001365<ref name=nrhp>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/oh/Cuyahoga/districts.html |title=National Register of Historical Places &ndash; Ohio(OH), Cuyahoga County |accessdate=2011-07-07 |work=National Register of Historic Places |publisher=Nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com}}</ref> | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = Privately maintained }} '''Nela Park''' is the headquarters of [[GE Lighting]], and is located in [[East Cleveland, Ohio|East Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]]. Today, GE Lighting is a part of [[GE Home & Business Solutions]], headquartered in [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Kentucky]]. Nela Park serves as the operating headquarters of GE Lighting.
The institute was first organized by entrepreneurs Franklin Terry and Burton Tremaine of the National Electric Lamp Company.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ech.cwru.edu/ech-cgi/article.pl?id=NP1 |title=Nela Park |work=The Encyclopedia of Cleveland History |date=June 27, 1997 |accessdate=October 20, 2013}}</ref> Development of the site was started in 1911, when the [[National Electric Lamp Association]] (NELA), formed by John Robert Crouse, Sr, J.B. Crouse, and H.A. Tremaine in 1901,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crouse.cromaine.org/crouse.asp |title=J. Robert Crouse, Sr. |work=Cromaine District Library |accessdate=March 3, 2015}}</ref> was dissolved and absorbed into [[General Electric]]. It was the first [[industrial park]] in the world,<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Nela Park |url=http://www.gelighting.com/na/business_lighting/education_resources/conferences/institute/history.htm |publisher=General Electric Company |accessdate=December 5, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127064708/http://www.gelighting.com/na/business_lighting/education_resources/conferences/institute/history.htm |archivedate=November 27, 2011 |df= }}</ref> and was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1975. The campus emulates a university setting, and the dominant architectural style is [[Georgian Revival]]. The {{convert|92|acre|m2|sing=on}} campus is home to GE's Lighting & Electrical Institute, which was founded in 1933. Each December, Nela Park features a world-famous Christmas lighting display, which culminates in a miniature version of the [[National Christmas Tree]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], designed by GE Lighting.
[[File:Albert Einstein and Ernest Fox Nichols Cleveland GE Nela Park 1922.jpg|thumb|left | In 1921, [[Albert Einstein]] visits Nela Park with [[Ernest Fox Nichols]].]]
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Nela Park 1975.png|thumb|250px|right|1975 An aerial view of Nela Park.]] --> == See also == * [[Marvin Pipkin]], scientist engineer that had many inventions and innovations for the light bulb and worked at NELA Park.<ref> *{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Kane|first=Joseph Nathan |title=Famous First Facts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PaYEAAAAYAAJ|year=1964|publisher=H. W. Wilson|quote=The first electric lamp bulb frosted on the inside with sufficient strength for commercial handling was invented by Marvin Pipkin of the Incandescent Lamp Department of the General Electric Company at Nela Park, Ohio. On June 29, 1925, he applied for a patent.}} </ref>
